<p>There have been a couple of articles lately, where the SMSM has been discussing the idea of Kyogo Furuhashi returning to Celtic.</p>
<p>Now, granted, this wouldn&#8217;t be the first time something like this could happen.</p>
<p>We&#8217;ve seen two examples of it already this season.</p>
<p>With Jota returning and the return of Kieran Tierney imminent at the end of the current season.</p>
<p>But a return for Kyogo?</p>
<p>I think it&#8217;s highly unlikely.</p>
<p>It&#8217;s unlikely for a few reasons, but the main one would be his shoulder injury.</p>
<p>There&#8217;s no doubting Celtic got away with one on that front.</p>
<p>I&#8217;m surprised it was picked up on during his medical for Rennes, but it was discussed in the media recently, and it would appear at the time, Rennes wanted him despite the threat of the injury hanging over the Japanese international.</p>
<p>Michael Nicholson is probably sitting in the Celtic boardroom, grinning to himself contentedly about that.</p>
<p>£10 million secured for a player who had an historic injury, and he is 30 years old.</p>
</div>
<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-celtic-definitely-came-out-of-that-deal-better-off-than-rennes-did" style="position: relative">Celtic definitely came out of that deal better off than Rennes did.</h3>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://cdn.readeverything.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/39/2025/03/GettyImages-2196302039-1.jpg" data-image="aqseokneh1g1" alt="(Photo by SEBASTIEN SALOM-GOMIS/AFP via Getty Images)"></p>
<p style="position: relative">Spare a thought for the Rennes board, though, when you consider they forked out £10 million for Kyogo, and now they have a manager who isn&#8217;t even interested in using him.</p>
<p style="position: relative">Obviously, they weren&#8217;t to know that at the time, as Kyogo was specifically chosen by the now sacked Jorge Sampaoli.</p>
<p style="position: relative">In the <a href="https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-transfer-news/kyogo-celtic-rennes-transfer-return-34866621">Record</a> this morning, they&#8217;ve once again gone all Football Insider, referencing the opinion of Marvin Bartley when it comes to the idea of a return to Celtic for Kyogo.</p>
<p style="position: relative">Before that, they detail how Habib Beye, the current Rennes manager, states that Kyogo is out of the picture due to his style of play.</p>
<p style="position: relative">Here, the Record picks up on the views of Beye on Kyogo:</p>
<blockquote class="wp-block-quote" style="position: relative">
<p>But speaking to the French outlet, Beye insisted that the fitness had not factored into his thinking about playing the frontman &#8211; who has made just four appearances since his Parkhead exit without scoring.</p>
<p>He insisted that the decision comes down to the way he wants his frontmen to play: Kyogo has different abilities from other strikers, he needs to have a focal point, because he&#8217;s very mobile.</p>
<p>He&#8217;s a combination player, and we&#8217;re working a lot at the moment on these notions of complementarity attack, so that he feels confident and fully involved.</p>
</blockquote>
<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-reading-that-it-highlights-another-reason-why-it-s-unlikely-a-return-to-celtic-would-be-on-the-cards-for-kyogo" style="position: relative">Reading that, it highlights another reason why it&#8217;s unlikely a return to Celtic would be on the cards for Kyogo.</h3>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://cdn.readeverything.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/39/2025/03/GettyImages-2195344422-1.jpg" data-image="5byigp3zxoo8" alt="(Photo by Ian MacNicol/Getty Images)"></p>
<p style="position: relative">I think it&#8217;s fair to say that his style of play didn&#8217;t fit into Brendan Rodgers&#8217; way of doing things either.</p>
<p style="position: relative">This was clearly evidenced by the sharp decline in the amount of goals he contributed after the departure of Ange Postecoglou.</p>
<p style="position: relative">In reality, Kyogo&#8217;s situation really is a hard luck story.</p>
<p style="position: relative">But ultimately, the striker stated he wanted to go to a club that would enhance his chances of playing in the next World Cup for Japan.</p>
<p style="position: relative">That&#8217;s understandable, but the move to Rennes has turned out to be a nightmare.</p>
<p style="position: relative">If anything, it has set back any chance he has of going to the World Cup with Japan.</p>
<p style="position: relative">While I feel sorry for Kyogo, he made his choice.</p>
<p style="position: relative">I wrote an <a href="https://readceltic.com/2025/03/08/matt-oriley-and-kyogo-are-proof-positive-that-the-urge-to-leave-celtic-for-for-bigger-and-better-things-doesnt-always-end-in-superstardom/">article</a> recently, where I stated the grass wasn&#8217;t always greener when you move away from Celtic.</p>
<p style="position: relative">I think Kyogo is the perfect example of that.</p>
<p style="position: relative">Despite what&#8217;s happened to him, it&#8217;s highly unlikely we&#8217;ll see him back at Celtic in the future.</p>
<p style="position: relative">Would I want him back?</p>
<p style="position: relative">He&#8217;s a player I always admired, but we need to be looking forward.</p>
<p style="position: relative">I think now, bringing him back would be backward step.</p>
<p style="position: relative">I wish him well for the future.</p>
<p style="position: relative">He had his time at Celtic.</p>
<p style="position: relative">But I don&#8217;t think a return would benefit either party now.</p>
